Use tabs to alternate between attributes belonging to, or strongly associated with, an instance of a particular
        object. Do
        not use them to navigate to the management of objects that are only associated with the type of your object.

E.g. Imagine that your "reports" have a set of "parameters" associated with each report, i.e. a parameter
        "Ordering Company"
        is a filter for the "Banana Orders" report. The reports also have a set of "report users" that are allowed to
        view
        any report, i.e. "John Smith" is allowed to see any of the reports. Note that "report users" are associated with
        "reports" in general, not one particular report. In this case, your Edit Report page might have a tab for
        parameters,
        but it should not have a tab for the report users. Instead, there should be a "Manage Report Users" page.

A combo box is a combination of a drop-down list or list box and a single-line editable textbox, allowing the user to either type a value directly or select a value from the list.

This p-control is used when you need to specify a value from a huge list of data, which is impractical to load the whole at a time on the client side.

BB Combo box supports server side data virtualisation - enables you to display large datasets by using a fixed amount of list items in the popup list of the ComboBox regardless of the dataset size.
When the list is scrolled, the ComboBox reuses the existing items to display the relevant data instead of creating new ones.

Note well: group membership rules and user interface vary radically between projects.
        For the purposes of the demo, the users 'manager-in-group-[x]@bbconsult.co.uk' have been created with group membership.

Group membership is the most typical of resource-based security constraints: if the user belongs to group X, and
        the resource belongs to group X then the user may see the resource.
It is not typical to make menu items dependent on group membership, but we demonstrate here that it is possible.
